    <div class="hero" id="vision">
        <div class="container">
            <h1>Here's Where Mississippi Stands.<br>Here's What's Possible.</h1>
            <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; text-align: center; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
                Every Mississippian deserves opportunity, security, and a voice in our state's future. This resource hub provides clear information about the challenges we face and practical solutions that can work for all of usâ€”regardless of where we live or what we believe.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="container">
        <section class="section" id="issues">
            <h2>The Issues Mississippians Face</h2>
            <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
                We can't solve problems we don't understand. Here are the real challenges facing our neighbors, backed by facts and told through our shared experiences.
            </p>
            
            <div class="issue-card">
                <h3>Economic Hardship: The Daily Struggle</h3>
                <div class="stat-highlight">
                    <strong>The Numbers Don't Lie:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
                        <li>Mississippi median household income: $48,716 (US average: $70,784)</li>
                        <li>19.4% of all Mississippians live in poverty (US average: 11.5%)</li>
                        <li>27.8% of Mississippi children live in poverty (highest in nation)</li>
                        <li>39% of Mississippi families are ALICE (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed)</li>
                        <li>Counties hit hardest: Holmes (34.7% poverty), Humphreys (31.2%), Jefferson (30.6%)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Sarah's Story - Yazoo City:</strong> Sarah works full-time at the chicken processing plant for $11.50/hour ($23,920/year). Her rent for a two-bedroom apartment is $750/month. After utilities ($180), car payment ($250), insurance ($120), and gas ($150), she has $470 left each month to feed and clothe her three kids, buy medicine when they're sick, and handle any emergency. Last month, her car broke down. The $400 repair meant choosing between fixing it to keep her job or buying groceries. The food bank helped, but she still had to send her kids to school hungry three days that week.
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>James's Reality - Clarksdale:</strong> James owns a small auto repair shop that his father started 40 years ago. He employs three people but can only pay them $10/hour because business has dropped 40% since the factory closed. He hasn't taken a salary in six months, living off his savings to keep his employees paid. He's one major equipment breakdown away from closing permanently.
                </div>
                
                <p><strong>The Ripple Effect:</strong> When families can't afford basics, local businesses lose customers. When businesses close, jobs disappear. When jobs disappear, young people leave. It's a cycle that's been draining Mississippi communities for decades. In the Delta alone, we've lost 68,000 residents since 2010â€”that's entire towns worth of teachers, nurses, entrepreneurs, and families.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="issue-card">
                <h3>Healthcare Access Crisis: Life and Death Decisions</h3>
                <div class="stat-highlight">
                    <strong>The Healthcare Desert:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
                        <li>12.4% uninsured rate (362,000 Mississippians without coverage)</li>
                        <li>6 rural hospitals closed since 2013, 36 more at risk</li>
                        <li>54 of 82 counties designated as medically underserved</li>
                        <li>Only 195 primary care physicians per 100,000 people (US average: 241)</li>
                        <li>Mississippi ranks 50th in overall health outcomes</li>
                        <li>Infant mortality: 8.8 per 1,000 births (worst in nation)</li>
                        <li>Maternal mortality: 37.4 deaths per 100,000 births (US average: 20.1)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Betty's Emergency - Humphreys County:</strong> When 68-year-old Betty had a stroke at 2 AM, her daughter drove 52 miles to the nearest hospital in Greenwood because Humphreys County lost its hospital in 2019. Those extra 30 minutes meant the difference between full recovery and permanent disability. Betty now needs round-the-clock care her family can't afford, and Medicare doesn't fully cover.
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Marcus's Diabetes - Indianola:</strong> Marcus, 45, has diabetes but no insurance. The nearest endocrinologist is 90 miles away in Jackson. He rations his insulin, buying it from Mexico online because it costs $340/month at the local pharmacy. Last year, rationing led to a diabetic coma. The emergency room visit cost $18,000. He'll never be able to pay it, and his credit is ruined.
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Pregnancy in the Delta:</strong> Ashley lives in Tunica and is six months pregnant. The nearest OB-GYN is 45 miles away in Memphis. She's missed three prenatal appointments because she couldn't afford gas and couldn't get time off work. Mississippi's Black mothers are 2.7 times more likely to die from pregnancy complications than white mothersâ€”Ashley worries she'll become a statistic.
                </div>
                
                <p><strong>The Human Cost:</strong> Every year, an estimated 300 Mississippians die from lack of health insurance. That's not just numbersâ€”that's somebody's parent, child, neighbor. Rural ambulance services are shutting down too. In Calhoun County, there's one ambulance for 14,500 people. If you have a heart attack during another emergency, you wait.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="issue-card">
                <h3>Education Emergency: Failing Our Future</h3>
                <div class="stat-highlight">
                    <strong>The Classroom Crisis:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
                        <li>3,036 certified teacher vacancies (5.4% of all positions)</li>
                        <li>Starting teacher salary: $37,000 (surrounding states: $42,000-$48,000)</li>
                        <li>32% of teachers leave within first 5 years</li>
                        <li>Only 35% of 4th graders read at grade level</li>
                        <li>Only 20% of 8th graders proficient in math</li>
                        <li>$3.8 billion in deferred maintenance on school buildings</li>
                        <li>147 schools rated "D" or "F" (serving 89,000 students)</li>
                        <li>Digital divide: 34% of students lack reliable internet for homework</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Ms. Johnson's Classroom - Jackson Public Schools:</strong> Ms. Johnson teaches 4th grade with 31 students, no aide, and textbooks from 2008. The ceiling leaks so badly she's arranged desks around the buckets. She spends $200 monthly of her $39,000 salary on basic supplies like pencils and paper. After her second job at Target and weekend tutoring, she makes ends meet, but she's exhausted. Five teachers at her school quit mid-year. "I love these kids," she says, "but I can't afford to keep teaching."
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Rural Consolidation - Kemper County:</strong> When East Kemper Elementary closed, 7-year-old Destiny's bus ride went from 20 minutes to 75 minutes each way. She leaves home at 5:45 AM and doesn't return until 5 PM. She's too tired for homework most nights, and her grades are slipping. Her mom can't helpâ€”she works two jobs and never finished high school herself.
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>The Digital Divide - Noxubee County:</strong> During COVID, Timothy had to sit in the McDonald's parking lot to use WiFi for virtual school. Even now, his homework requires internet the family can't afford ($140/month for satellite internet is their only option). His teacher prints extra copies, but Timothy knows he's falling behind kids in towns with broadband.
                </div>
                
                <p><strong>Long-term Impact:</strong> Mississippi students who don't read proficiently by 3rd grade are four times more likely to drop out. Our 17% dropout rate means 5,100 students leave school each year without diplomas. Their lifetime earnings will be $300,000 less than graduates. That's $1.5 billion in lost economic potential every single year.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="issue-card">
                <h3>Infrastructure Collapse: The Systems We Depend On</h3>
                <div class="stat-highlight">
                    <strong>Failing Grade Report Card:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
                        <li>Roads: 'D' grade - 27% in poor condition, $6.8 billion backlog</li>
                        <li>Bridges: 1,295 structurally deficient (10% of all bridges)</li>
                        <li>Drinking Water: 'D+' grade - systems average 67 years old</li>
                        <li>Jackson water crisis affected 180,000 people for 6+ months</li>
                        <li>450+ boil water notices issued annually statewide</li>
                        <li>Wastewater: 348 systems violating EPA standards</li>
                        <li>Broadband: 383,000 Mississippians lack any internet access</li>
                        <li>Electric Grid: 3rd highest outage rate nationally</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>The Jackson Water Crisis - Personal Impact:</strong> For six months, the Williams family couldn't drink, cook with, or bathe in tap water. They spent $400 monthly on bottled water. Their restaurant, Williams' Soul Food, lost $75,000 in revenue and laid off 8 employees. Their daughter missed 15 days of school when buildings closed for lack of water. "We're not just talking about inconvenience," Mr. Williams says. "This destroyed businesses and lives."
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Bridge Fear - Sharkey County:</strong> The Highway 14 bridge over Steele Bayou is so deteriorated that school buses take a 20-mile detour. Parents drive separately because they won't put multiple family members on it at once. Emergency vehicles can't use it, adding 15 minutes to response times. The county says repairs need $3 million they don't have.
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Small Town Sewage - Belzoni:</strong> When it rains, raw sewage backs up into homes in Belzoni's historic Black neighborhood. The system is 80 years old. Families place their furniture on blocks, knowing the next storm will bring contamination. Children play in yards where sewage surfaces. The EPA fined the city, but fines don't fix pipesâ€”the $45 million needed for repairs equals 15 years of the entire city budget.
                </div>
                
                <p><strong>Economic Drain:</strong> Poor infrastructure costs the average Mississippi driver $637 annually in vehicle repairs and wasted fuel. Businesses won't locate where water isn't reliable or broadband doesn't exist. We're literally watching our competitive advantage crumble beneath us.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="issue-card">
                <h3>Racial Disparities: Two Mississippis</h3>
                <div class="stat-highlight">
                    <strong>The Inequality Gap:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">
                        <li>Median household income: White: $58,500 / Black: $31,300</li>
                        <li>Poverty rate: White: 11.8% / Black: 30.4%</li>
                        <li>Unemployment: White: 3.2% / Black: 7.8%</li>
                        <li>Homeownership: White: 74% / Black: 42%</li>
                        <li>Infant mortality per 1,000: White: 5.9 / Black: 11.8</li>
                        <li>Life expectancy: White: 75.8 years / Black: 71.3 years</li>
                        <li>College graduation: White: 36% / Black: 21%</li>
                        <li>Incarceration rate: Mississippi has highest rate nationally, 71% are Black despite being 38% of population</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Two Schools, One Town - Greenville:</strong> Washington School (95% white) has a robotics lab, new computers, and AP classes. Coleman High (96% Black), three miles away, has no AP physics, broken heating, and textbooks held together with duct tape. Both are public schools in the same district. The difference? Washington's PTA raises $200,000 annually. Coleman's raises $3,000. Property valuesâ€”and thus local school fundingâ€”reflect decades of residential segregation.
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Banking Desert - West Jackson:</strong> When the last bank branch left West Jackson (87% Black), residents lost more than ATMs. Ms. Robinson now pays $7 to cash her paycheck at a check-cashing store, $5 per money order for bills, and 400% APR at payday lenders for emergencies. The same $500 emergency that costs someone with banking access $15 in overdraft fees costs Ms. Robinson $200 in payday loan interest.
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Environmental Injustice - North Gulfport:</strong> Turkey Creek, a historic Black community, floods constantly while adjacent white neighborhoods stay dry. Why? Infrastructure investments went elsewhere for decades. Now developers want the land, offering buyouts at fraction of fair value. "They ignored us when we needed help," says lifelong resident Charles Evans. "Now they want us gone when the land's valuable."
                </div>
                
                <p><strong>Generational Impact:</strong> These disparities compound over generations. A Black child born in Mississippi today has a 45% chance of experiencing poverty, compared to 13% for a white child. Without intervention, these children face vastly different futures based solely on raceâ€”a moral and economic failure that costs Mississippi billions in unrealized potential.</p>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <section class="section" id="solutions">
            <h2>Practical Solutions & How They Work</h2>
            <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
                These aren't pie-in-the-sky ideas. They're specific, funded, proven solutions organized by implementation timeline and backed by real success stories.
            </p>
            
            <div class="solution-card">
                <h3>1. Education Revolution: Building Mississippi's Future</h3>
                
                <h4><span class="category-label immediate">Immediate Win</span> Teacher Emergency Response (Year 1)</h4>
                <p><strong>The Plan:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>$50,000 minimum salary immediately</strong> - Requires $385 million annually</li>
                    <li><strong>$10,000 signing bonuses</strong> for critical shortage areas (math, science, special ed)</li>
                    <li><strong>Student loan forgiveness</strong> - $5,000/year for 4 years in Title I schools</li>
                    <li><strong>Rural teacher housing</strong> - Partner with USDA to provide $400/month rental homes near schools</li>
                    <li><strong>Emergency retention bonuses</strong> - $2,500 for every current teacher who stays</li>
                </ul>
                
                <div class="funding-box">
                    <strong>How We Pay:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Reallocate $200M from administrative overhead (Mississippi spends 18% above national average on administration)</li>
                        <li>Use $100M in federal COVID education recovery funds (available through 2024)</li>
                        <li>Lottery education proceeds: $85M annually currently underutilized</li>
                        <li>Total Year 1 Cost: $385M (5.5% increase to education budget)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Proven Success - Alabama:</strong> When Alabama raised starting teacher pay to $47,500 in 2022, teacher applications increased 31% in one year. Shortage areas saw 45% more applicants. Rural districts that couldn't fill positions for years had multiple candidates per opening. Birmingham schools report 89% teacher retention, up from 74%.
                </div>
                
                <p><strong>Expected Impact for Mississippi:</strong></p>
                <div>
                    <span class="impact-metric">2,000+ teacher vacancies filled in Year 1</span>
                    <span class="impact-metric">Class sizes reduced by 20%</span>
                    <span class="impact-metric">$450M economic boost from teacher spending</span>
                </div>
                
                <h4><span class="category-label strategic">Strategic Investment</span> 21st Century Learning (Years 2-5)</h4>
                <p><strong>The Comprehensive Upgrade:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Universal Pre-K rollout</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Phase 1 (Year 2): 25 highest-poverty districts - $125M</li>
                            <li>Phase 2 (Year 3): 25 additional districts - $125M</li>
                            <li>Phase 3 (Year 4-5): Statewide completion - $250M</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Innovation Labs in every high school</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>3D printers, robotics equipment, coding computers</li>
                            <li>Partner with Mississippi businesses for $50M in equipment donations</li>
                            <li>Train 500 teachers in STEM instruction</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Career Academies</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Healthcare pathway with UMMC: 2,000 students/year</li>
                            <li>Advanced manufacturing with Nissan/Toyota: 1,500 students/year</li>
                            <li>Agriculture tech with Mississippi State: 1,000 students/year</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Literacy Coaches</strong> - One for every elementary school (425 positions)</li>
                </ul>
                
                <div class="funding-box">
                    <strong>Strategic Funding Sources:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Federal Preschool Development Grants: $150M over 3 years</li>
                        <li>Corporate partnerships (commitments from Entergy, C Spire, BankPlus): $50M</li>
                        <li>Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act: $75M annually</li>
                        <li>21st Century Community Learning Centers: $40M annually</li>
                        <li>Total 4-Year Investment: $750M ($187.5M/year)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>North Carolina Success Story:</strong> Their Career and College Promise program, connecting high schools with community colleges, saw 65,000 students earn college credit while in high school. Participants were 24% more likely to graduate college. The state saved families $130 million in tuition costs. Manufacturing companies report 40% better-prepared entry-level workers.
                </div>
                
                <h4><span class="category-label transformational">Transformational Change</span> Complete Infrastructure Overhaul (10-Year Plan)</h4>
                <p><strong>Rebuilding from the Ground Up:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Phase 1 (Years 1-3): Emergency Repairs</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Fix roofs, HVAC, and safety hazards in 200 worst buildings - $600M</li>
                            <li>Provide temporary modular classrooms where needed - $100M</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Phase 2 (Years 4-7): Modernization</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Build 50 new schools in growing areas - $2B</li>
                            <li>Complete renovation of 300 existing schools - $1.5B</li>
                            <li>Technology infrastructure (fiber optic to every school) - $200M</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Phase 3 (Years 8-10): Innovation Centers</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Regional STEM centers (6 locations) - $300M</li>
                            <li>Arts and humanities centers (4 locations) - $200M</li>
                            <li>Agricultural research facilities (3 locations) - $150M</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                
                <div class="funding-box">
                    <strong>10-Year Funding Strategy:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>State bond issue (AAA rating allows 2.5% interest): $2B</li>
                        <li>Federal infrastructure funds earmarked for schools: $1.2B</li>
                        <li>Public-private partnerships (naming rights, equipment): $300M</li>
                        <li>Energy savings from efficiency upgrades: $150M over 10 years</li>
                        <li>Land sales from consolidated properties: $100M</li>
                        <li>Total: $4.85B over 10 years ($485M annually)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
