                <h3>6. Racial Equity: Justice and Opportunity</h3>
                
                <h4><span class="category-label immediate">Immediate Win</span> Economic Justice Initiative</h4>
                <p><strong>Closing the Wealth Gap:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Minority Business Acceleration</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>$25M dedicated loan fund at 2% interest</li>
                            <li>State contracts: 25% to minority-owned businesses</li>
                            <li>Free business incubators in majority-Black cities</li>
                            <li>Mentorship matching with established businesses</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Banking Access Program</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Partner with credit unions for branches in banking deserts</li>
                            <li>State-backed micro-loans up to $10,000</li>
                            <li>Financial literacy mandatory in high schools</li>
                            <li>Ban on predatory payday lending (cap at 36% APR)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Property Tax Reform</strong>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Reassess properties to fix decades of discriminatory assessments</li>
                            <li>Circuit breaker limiting tax to 2% of income for seniors</li>
                            <li>Heir property legal assistance to prevent land loss</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                
                <div class="example-box">
                    <strong>Jackson Success Story:</strong> Farish Street entrepreneur Cassandra Williams received a $15,000 minority business loan to open a soul food restaurant. She now employs 12 people, bought the building next door for expansion, and mentors three other Black women starting businesses. "Access to capital changed everything," she says. "Not charityâ€”just a fair chance."
